Low Complexity Enhancement Video Coding
Main Idea of LCEVC
Instead of replacing existing codecs like:
x264
x265
AOMedia Video 1
LCEVC adds an enhancement layer on top of a base codec.

Basic Principle
Original Video
       ↓
Low-Resolution Base Encode
       ↓
Enhancement Residual Layer
       ↓
LCEVC Reconstruction
       ↓
High-Quality Output

The base codec compresses:
Lower-resolution video
LCEVC then:
Restores detail
Enhances quality
Improves sharpness

Why LCEVC Was Developed
Modern codecs like:
HEVC
AV1
VVC

provide high compression efficiency but suffer from:
Very high computational complexity
Expensive encoding
Large power consumption
Difficult real-time deployment

LCEVC attempts to solve this.
Adds residual corrections
using lightweight processing.

Key Objectives
1. Lower Computational Complexity
Can use:
Simpler base encoder
Lower-resolution encoding

Result:
Faster encoding

2. Better Compression Efficiency
Achieves:
Better quality at same bitrate
or
Lower bitrate at same quality

3. Real-Time Streaming Support
Useful for:
Live streaming
Esports
Mobile streaming
Cloud gaming

4. Hardware Compatibility
Works with existing decoder hardware.
This is a major advantage.

Architecture
Two-Layer System
A. Base Layer
Encoded using conventional codec:
AVC
HEVC
AV1
at reduced resolution.

B. Enhancement Layer
Contains:
Residual detail information
Sharpening enhancement
Reconstruction guidance
Very lightweight compared to full codec complexity.

Example Workflow
Suppose:
Final output required = 4K
Traditional approach:
Encode full 4K HEVC
LCEVC approach:
Encode 1080p base layer
Add enhancement layer
Reconstruct near-4K quality

Benefits:
Lower complexity
Faster encoding
Lower bandwidth

Comparison with Traditional Codecs
| Feature                | Traditional Codec | LCEVC  |
| ---------------------- | ----------------- | ------ |
| Complexity             | High              | Lower  |
| Encoding Speed         | Slower            | Faster |
| Hardware Requirement   | Heavy             | Lower  |
| Real-Time Capability   | Difficult         | Better |
| Enhancement Layer      | No                | Yes    |
| Backward Compatibility | Limited           | Good   |

Important Components
1. Upscaling
Base layer is upscaled to target resolution.

2. Residual Enhancement
Enhancement data corrects:
Blur
Missing texture
Compression artifacts

3. Lightweight Processing
Uses:
Simple filtering
Low-complexity enhancement tools
instead of extremely complex prediction structures.

